@Node "Glossary"

@{b}APPENDIX C - GLOSSARY@{ub}

@{b}Alignment @{ub}- See Justification.

@{b}Backspace @{ub}- Backspace has two meanings in InterWord.  If you press the backspace key on its own, it will delete the character to the left of the cursor.  If you select the @{b}Backspace @{ub}option from the @{b}Layout @{ub}menu, it moves the cursor back one position, and lets you overlay one character on another, thus creating a combination of both.  The combined character will only be visible when it is printed.

@{b}Current @{ub}- This expression mainly applies when talking about the status of a document.  InterWord can handle up to 50 of them at a time, or which two may be visible simultaneously.  However, obviously you can only physically work on one document at a time.  Whichever one the cursor resides in, is known as the current document.  All menu, mouse and keyboard operations only apply to the current document.

@{b}Cursor @{ub}- The cursor is the small flashing block or line that indicates where text will appear on the screen when a key is pressed.

@{b}Cycle Gadget @{ub}- A cycle gadget offers you a way of choosing one of numerous options without having to display all of them at once.  Each time you click the gadget, the next option is displayed, and when you are happy with the current option, simply stop clicking it.

@{b}Delete @{ub}- Like backspace, delete has two meanings.  If you simply press the Del key, the character beneath the cursor will be erased.  Alternatively, you can highlight a block of text and select @{b}Delete @{ub}from the @{b}Edit @{ub}menu, erasing the entire block.  Once text has been deleted, it cannot be recovered.  If you select a file name, then select @{b}Delete @{ub}from the @{b}Disk Operations @{ub}menu, the file will be permanently erased.

@{b}Document @{ub}- Document is the name given to any text created or stored in InterWord, from a single letter to a one hundred page manual.  It's a simple generic term used as a substitute for all other expressions (such as manuscript, essay, letter, paper, thesis, report, etc) which are used to describe a piece of writing.

@{b}File Name @{ub}- The identifying title given to any file stored on disk or in RAM, regardless of its type.  File names are obviously essential so that you can distinguish one file from another.

@{b}Gadget @{ub}- Although the word gadget may have various meanings according to the program being used, in InterWord a gadget is a button that performs a particular function when clicked upon using the mouse.

@{b}Highlight @{ub}- A highlight is simply a way of indicating that something has been selected, be it a block of text or a menu option.  Highlights are usually shown in inverted (negative) colours.

@{b}Hyphen @{ub}- Hyphens are small horizontal dashes like this '-', and they serve two purposes.  Their primary purpose is grammatical, because they are used instead of a space to link two words together to form an accepted expression.  For example, bit-map, 24-bit, high-tech, etc.

     Their other purpose is to break up long words which would otherwise form the first word of a new line, resulting in unnecessary spaces in the line above.

     For example, here's a piece of text, without and with hyphenation.
@{i}InterWord is an interesting program, that deserves great distinction.
In-ter-Word is an in-ter-est-ing pro-gram, that de-ser-ves great dis-tinc-tion.@{ui}

@{b}Icon @{ub}- An icon is a small picture designed to illustrate its function or contents.

@{b}Justification @{ub}- Justification describes the way that text is aligned on the page in relation to the page margins.  In other words, should the text be lined up with the left or right margins, or both, or should it perhaps be aligned with the centre of the screen so that the ends of the text are equidistant from each margin.

@{b}Keyboard short-cut @{ub}- A combination of keys, which when pressed, perform a function or operation that would otherwise require use of the mouse and usually a menu selection.

@{b}LIX @{ub}- An acronym for Legibility IndeX.  LIX is a way of quickly assessing how easy a document is to read and understand.

@{b}Load @{ub}- To transfer a file or document from disk or RAM and into InterWord's work memory.

@{b}Mail Merge @{ub}- The automatic incorporation of text from a data or mail merge file directly into a document as it is printed, thus creating customised letters containing personalised text, without actually entering the personal text by hand.  If the data or mail merge file contains multiple records, multiple documents may be printed, each of which contains unique text.

@{b}Margin @{ub}- A page has absolute dimensions beyond which text cannot be printed, either because the printer's heads cannot move any further or because if they could, they would be printing off the edge of the paper.  Margins are user-defined borders within the absolute dimensions of the page, which create areas of white space around a document both on the screen, and on paper.

@{b}Markers @{ub}- Sometimes known as Tags or Style Tags, markers are invisible codes hidden in the text of a document to activate and deactivate certain functions.  All of the following operations use markers: margins, tabs, text styling (bold, italics, etc), return (line feed), Forced form feed, justification, changes in front, size changes etc.

@{b}Paragraph Indent @{ub}- Although modern typography often requires that paragraphs are only separated by a blank line, conventional grammar dictates that the first word of each new paragraph should be indented slightly from the main body of the text.  The amount of indentation varies, but three to five characters is common.

@{b}Pointer @{ub}- The small red arrow controlled by the mouse and use to make selections from menus or on-screen text.

@{b}Requester @{ub}- Any window which appears and requires you to take some action.

@{b}Save @{ub}- In InterWord, save means to store the current document on disk or in RAM (Random Access Memory).

@{b}Style tag @{ub}- A Merger which indicates that the appearance of subsequent text has been modified.  Text styles include bold, underline and superscript.

@{b}Tab @{ub}- You can think of a tab as a way for easily columnating or aligning text.  Tab markers (small downward facing triangles) may be placed on the Tab Rack, and when the Tab key is pressed, the cursor will jump to the next marker.  If there are no more markers, the cursor will move to the start of the next line.  Although pressing Tab essentially achieves the same result as pressing the space bar until the cursor is in position, tab markers only occupy a single character's worth of space.  Therefore, if you delete one, any text positioned by the tab will return to the point on the page where the tab key was originally pressed.

@{b}Tags @{ub}- See Markers

@{b}Text gadget/requester @{ub}- Text gadgets and requesters appear when you need to enter some text so that InterWord can perform an operation.  For example, when you select @{b}Page Number @{ub}from the @{b}Layout @{ub}menu, a text gadget/requester appears so that you can enter the starting page number.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

